{{Sex and the Law}}
The '''fantasy defense''' is where a defendant accused of attempting a crime (enticing [[Minor (law)|minors]] into sexual activity, for example) claims that they never intended to complete the crime. Instead, they claim they were engaged in a fantasy and, in the case of luring a minor, believed they were dealing with an adult.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ferraro|first=Monique Mattei|title=Investigating Child Exploitation and Pornography: The Internet, the Law and Forensic Science|year=2005|publisher=[[Academic Press]]|isbn=978-0-12-163105-5|page=283|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BtjzJhcAAGYC&lpg=PA283&dq=%22Fantasy%20defense%22%20-Android%20-football%20-itunes%20-wikipedia%20-game%20-football&pg=PA283#v=onepage&q&f=false|author2=Casey, Eoghan|accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref>
The fantasy defense was developed by Donald B. Marks, the attorney for [[Patrick Naughton]],<ref>{{cite web|title=In the Media|url=http://www.marksandbrooklier.com/In-The-Media.aspx#DisneyInternetExecutivesDefense|publisher=Los Angeles Criminal Defense Law Firm|accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> the [[Disney]] executive who eventually pleaded guilty to traveling in interstate commerce with the intent to have sex with a minor, in violation of [[Ages of consent in North America#Federal laws|18 U.S.C. §&nbsp;2423(b)]].<ref name="CBS The Fantasy Defense">{{cite news| url = http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2000/05/24/eveningnews/main199192.shtml| title = The Fantasy Defense| publisher = [[CBS News]]| date = 2000-05-31| accessdate = 2009-08-02}}</ref><ref name="Prosecuting Cyber-Pedophiles">{{cite journal|last=Yamagami|first=Donald S.|title=Prosecuting Cyber-Pedophiles: How Can Intent Be Shown in a Virtual World in Light of the Fantasy Defense?|journal=[[Santa Clara Law Review]]|date=2000|volume=41|issue=2|url=http://digitalcommons.law.scu.edu/lawreview/vol41/iss2/6/|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref><ref name="PROFILING ONLINE SEX OFFENDERS, CYBER-PREDATORS, AND PEDOPHILES">{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Kimberly|title=Profiling Online Sex Offenders, Cyber-Predators, and Pedophiles|journal=Journal of Behavioral Profiling|year=2005|volume=5|issue=1|url=http://www.netaddiction.com/articles/Pedophile.pdf|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> The "fantasy defense" used in the Naughton case was novel; however, since the closely watched Naughton fantasy defense was successful, defense lawyers were expected to use it to help other clients.<ref name="Prosecuting Cyber-Pedophiles" />
